04488nam a22006975i 9780520313231DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203132317 a10.1525/97805203132312doi  a(DE-B1597)569299  a(OCoLC)1198929472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPS3523.E7994 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813.521 aGraver, Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Obsession with Anne Frank :bMeyer Levin and the Diary /cLawrence Graver.  a"A Centennial book", Reprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tPREFACE and ACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. "Some day a teller would arise" -- t2. The Old Jewish Question -- t3. Levin's Anne Frank -- t4. The Fanatic, Anne Frank in Israel, and The Obsession -- t5. Don Quixote and the Star of David -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnne Frank's Diary has been acclaimed throughout the world as an indelible portrait of a gifted girl and as a remarkable document of the Holocaust. For Meyer Levin, the respected writer who helped bring the Diary to an American audience, the Jewish girl's moving story became a thirty-year obsession that altered his life and brought him heartbreaking sorrow. Lawrence Graver's fascinating account of Meyer Levin's ordeal is a story within a story. What began as a warm collaboration between Levin and Anne's father, Otto Frank, turned into a notorious dispute that lasted several decades and included litigation and public scandal. Behind this story is another: one man's struggle with himself--as a Jew and as a writer--in postwar America. Looming over both stories is the shadow of the Holocaust and its persistent, complex presence in our lives. Graver's book is based on hundreds of unpublished documents and on interviews with some of the Levin-Frank controversy's major participants. It illuminates important areas of American culture: publishing, law, religion, politics, and the popular media. The "Red Scare," anti-McCarthyism, and the commercial imperatives of Broadway are all players in this book, along with the assimilationist mood among many Jews and the simplistic pieties of American society in the 1950s. Graver also examines the different and often conflicting ways that people the world over, Jewish and Gentile, wanted Anne Frank and her much-loved book to be represented. That her afterlife has in extraordinary ways taken on the shape and implications of myth makes Graver's story--and Meyer Levin's--even more compelling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in literature. 0aJewsxPublic opinion. 4aDiaspora. 4aHolocaust. 4aJewish history. 4aJewish studies. 4aJudaism. 4aShoah. 4aantisemitism. 4aassimilation. 4abiography. 4ahistory of Judaism. 4ahistory of jews outside Israel. 4ahistory. 4apogrom. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052030873240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520313231?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520313231423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520313231/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles